default&#xa0;defaultQ3. Have you changed you spread rates? If so, why?default28 of the 63 responses,
default or 44%, have altered their spread rates over the last 4 years
default.  Bearing in mind updates to Chapter 13 and Appendix H of Well Maintained Highways and recommendations in the Quarmby Report, it is unsurprising that a large number of local authorities have al
defaulttered spread rates. This was given as the main reason for altering the rates with other reasons being growing confidence in the products used meaning rates could be reduced and the need to conserve salt at times of heavy snow fall. One reason for not alter
defaulting rates was that some older gritters do not have the capacity for precision adjustment.      
default&#xa0;defaultQ4. Have you changed your storage arrangements? If so why?default38 local authorities, or 60% of responses, have changed their storage arrangements. These changes include building new storage barns both in existing depots and at new depots. 
defaultThere have been a number of new builds reflecting the level of investment in th
defaulte service with some councils building more than one. The alteration and extension of existing barns is also a change noted by a number of responses and putting roofs on salt bays is another example of investment.
defaultSheeting has been more widely adopted by lo
defaultcal authorities as an alternative to barn
defaults
default.
default The sheeting maintains quality as well as reducing environmental risks. 
defaultThis enables more flexible coverage but one local authority raised the issue of health and safety concerns when plastic sheets were being pu
defaultt on and off. This concern led them to build a barn instead.
defaultOther responses include quarries now being used for strategic stock piles, sharing of Highways Agency depots and use of the South East Wales storage facility. 
default Some have split their stocks and store it at non-operational sites. 
defaultOne has 4 new stockpiles at non-operationa
defaultl sites and these piles are 
defaultshipped to operational depots as needed or for summer restock to ensure the rotation of the stock as it may be held f
defaultor 3 or 4 years before use.
defaultSome have found further space within existing depots whilst others have purchased equipment to enable them to pile salt higher so fitting more salt into barns.
defaultThe general approach 
defaultwhich has been adopted over the past 4 years by
default many local authorities 
defaultis that all salt should be covered and a number of methods are being utilised to accomplish this. 
defaultS
defaultome 
defaultlocal authorities use a mixture of sheeting, existing and new barns and sharing other organisations storage facilities. 
defaultHowever 
defaultsome still leave 100% of their salt uncovered with no plans to change this arrangement.  
default2
default5 local authorities have not changed their storage arrangements and these will no doubt have a range of storage options in place
default including leaving salt uncovered and
default open to the elements
