defaultPI 112 Km length of footways where pdefaultrecautionary gritting was undertakendefaultA number of responses to the survey commented on the extra attention paid to salting footways and this is borne out by Performance Networks data. There was a dramatic increase in 2011-12 and no doubt this will be increa
defaultsed further in 2012-13. This will be as a result both of expanded routes and new equipment increasing productivity. 
default2008-09default19 kmdefault2009-10default15 kmdefault2010-11default14 kmdefault2011-12default61 kmdefault&#xa0;defaultConclusionsdefaultThis survey covered a 4 year period and as such includes a wide range of developments within local authorities. It highlights the breadth of changes which have been made to services including significant investments, the use of new materials, engagement wi
defaultth the public and discussions with councillors amongst others.  Of course some local authorities will have undertaken changes some years ago whilst others are just catching up. 
defaultWhat does emerge is a sector which perennially reviews elements of the service
default such as routes and salt stock levels and has enabled service improvement with a number of innovations and initiatives. Severe weather has forced the service to remain aware of developments by suppliers also and only 1 or 2 of the 63 responses provided det
defaultails of no changes whatsoever to the way their services are arranged. 
defaultThe development of winter plans as part of emergency planning arrangements reflect the corporate approach to the issue which inc
defaultludes
default cross departmental action, allied to work with othe
defaultr public sector providers and other local organisations. Winter maintenance is no longer a reactive response by the highways department to a one off snow incident.
defaultThe call for collaboration in public services is being acted upon by some of the local autho
defaultrities who took part in this survey. Joint arrangements to procure salt, storage of salt stocks in other organisations depots and finance provided by other public organisations are examples. 
defaultFinancial questions will continue to arise with regard to this s
defaultervice area. Snow and ice create problems in 
defaultterms of highway and footway surfaces
default which lead to deterioration in the surface, cracks and
default potholes. Therefore it is imperative that snow, ice and water are removed from the highway as quickly as possible whic
defaulth reflects the importance of the service. Nonetheless all of the snow and ice which accumulates can never be removed which means the condition of the highway and footway (and drainage systems) needs to be in top condition so that water can’t begin the proc
defaultess of deterioration. This is of course a circular argument – the roads and footways need to be well maintained to avoid the worst outcomes of snow and ice. 
defaultThis is the perennial discussion highways engineers put forward at budget time highlighting the im
defaultportance of asset management, planned maintenance and the economic value of the network. 
defaultAs noted above, it will be interesting to see how winter maintenance budgets fare over the next few years if the weather is far less severe than over the last 4 years
default.
